After many months of using Rust - I was going back thru "The Rust Programming Language (book)" implementing the guessing game.  

I tried this code:

```rust
// .....
fn main() {
 10     println!("Guess the numer!");
  9
  8     let secret_number = rand::thread_rng().gen_range(1,101);
  7     println!("The secret number is: {}", secret_number);
  6
  5     println!("Please input your guess.");
  4
  3     let mut guess = String::new();
  2
  1     loop {
16          io::stdin().read_line(&mut guess).expect("Failed to read line");
  1         let guess:u32 = guess.trim().parse().expect("Please type a number!");
  2
  3
  4         println!("You guessed: {}", guess);
  5
  6         match guess.cmp(&secret_number) {
  7             Ordering::Less => println!("Too small!"),
  8             Ordering::Greater => println!("Too big!"),
  9             Ordering::Equal => {println!("You win!"); break;},
 10         }
 11     }
 12 }
 // ....
```
There is a bug in the above code which after finding it I thought Rust would have / should have caught?  Correct me if I'm wrong.

The program compiles fine with no warnings or errors.  When I run the program - I answer the the question to deliberately get it wrong - I am informed that the answer is wrong.

Then the guess variable is shadowed in the loop, the program compiles fine, then crashes at runtime after guessing a number a SECOND time.

If I circumvent the loop ( NO LOOP) as in the code below by just calling two iterations worth of read_line() then the program properly fails at compile time.
```rust
//    loop {
    1         io::stdin().read_line(&mut guess).expect("Failed to read line");
    2         let guess:u32 = guess.trim().parse().expect("Please type a number!");
    3
    4
    5
    6         println!("You guessed: {}", guess);
    7
    8         match guess.cmp(&secret_number) {
    9             Ordering::Less => println!("Too small!"),
   10             Ordering::Greater => println!("Too big!"),
   11             Ordering::Equal => {println!("You win!"); },
   12         }
>> 13         io::stdin().read_line(&mut guess).expect("Failed to read line");
>> 14         let guess:u32 = guess.trim().parse().expect("Please type a number!");
   15 //    }
```

The problem: when in a loop - it passes compilation - 
   I expect that it should NOT pass compilation and should raise the same compilation error as if there were NO loop.

If I'm wrong - I apologize ahead of time.
